Most nights I play KSP for a couple of hours after my son goes to sleep. Launching this station had me obsessed for several weeks. During that time I was unable to orbit any craft, such was my obsession. It went through many designs and failures. Ulitimately, it was launched manually, using ASAS during the orbital burn. What you see was launched in one piece.

The storage capacity of the station's tanks is between 6 and 7 thousand LFO. it will be fully kermanned with a crew of 12. it has 2600+ battery capacity and a high bandwidth communications array of 9 communotrons. the station has 12 docking ports 7.5k in MP reserves and a safety ladder along the length of each pylon. The station will serve as a staging/refueling area for missions to the Mun, Minimus and beyond. Its open structure radiates around a central docking port which will facilitate the assembly of large deep space mission vehicles.

Mods used are Nova Punch parts pack, Deep space mission pack and the JARFR tri hexagonal struts.

First space station, the ever-so-creatively-named Utility Station Alpha. In practice, less of a utility, more of an orbital lag-cannon. Hanging off the side like some bizarre alien robot leech is the MOT-3, or Manned Orbital Tug, affectionately nicknamed the "Ugly Duckling." The tug was orders of magnitude more useful than the station. Entering physics distance of this thing caused my fairly powerful PC to lurch to a halt.

And THIS is what happens to Not Very Helpful Space Stations (NVHSS).

*****

Bigger and better things ahead. Next station is under construction, using the Temstar Olympus and its companion modules as its core. Carrying a full Big Orange and an orbital warehouse, the Spacedock Hephaestus will soon be churning out spacecraft far too large to send up from a terrestrial launch vehicle. Next module going up is the PME Zeus, then after increasing orbital altitude the first shipments of parts can be sent up. Rendezvous is a little tricky when the station sits in a 73km orbit.

Jeb, get back inside before gravity sucks you down.

MOSS (Mun Orbital Science Station) with SSTMO Spirit of Prescott docked on the bottom of the multi-direction node and the Kerbin-return shuttle docked on top. On the end node is a non-functional Mun bus that is being used as a fuel depot (until it runs out). The transfer stage fuel tank and injection engine are still attached on the right end. Currently 6 Kerbals are onboard with two more en-route (kind of) in SSTMO Spirit of Sedona and an additional two Mun-side in the base that MOSS supports, Lonely Outpost.

For something a little bit different: the Stargazer Array

And now, due to some sort of strange error causing Spirit of Prescott to spawn inside MOSS, Spirit of Prescott is on the Mun (save file edit). Hopefully MOSS is still intact.
